\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination of the lower limbs reveals weakness in dorsiflexion and eversion of the right foot. There is no sensory loss, and reflexes are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is most likely affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibularis brevis","Fibularis longus","Fibularis tertius","Plantaris","Soleus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efibularis tertius\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is responsible for dorsiflexion and eversion of the foot. Weakness in these movements, as described in the stem, suggests an issue with this muscle. The fibularis tertius is often involved in activities that require lifting the front of the foot, such as running, and can be strained with increased activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efibularis longus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Efibularis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E muscles are primarily involved in eversion and plantarflexion, not dorsiflexion, making them less likely to be the source of the problem in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esoleus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is a plantarflexor of the foot and is not involved in dorsiflexion or eversion, so it is unlikely to be affected here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eplantaris\u003C/strong\u003E muscle, while it can assist in plantarflexion, is a small and often vestigial muscle that does not significantly contribute to dorsiflexion or eversion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The fibularis tertius muscle is involved in dorsiflexion and eversion of the foot.","Injury to the fibularis tertius can result in difficulty with these movements, affecting gait."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18342"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T09:43:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T14:53:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11060"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79331"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":nu